segments.text: Dr. Vandiver, would you please tell us your name?
Frank Everson Vandiver, born Austin, Texas, December 9, 1925.
And what happened after that?
67 years passed after that.
Your father was a professor?
He was a math professor at Texas, University of Texas.
and was on the faculty for 40 years, so I'm a faculty brat.
And I took my master's degree at the University of Texas, have no bachelor's degree, and went on and took my PhD in history at Tulane.
Who did you work under at Tulane?
Wendell Holmes Stevens.
OK, that's true.
Great man.
And spent some time teaching the summers at LSU, trying to fill in for T. Harry Williams.
which was never an easy job, as you can well imagine.
And was at Rice University for 24 years.
Went to Rice in 1955 and left in really the end of 1979.
And you taught primarily the South?
South and seminars in biography and civil war, that sort of thing.
And I also taught a freshman U.S. history course, which I greatly enjoyed.
Which I still enjoy.
I think it's a great course.
Everybody ought to teach it.
Each time I teach it, I learn more American history, don't you?
You really do.
It's wonderful.
And that's where you recruit the students of the future.
I shared the course every once in a while with Bill Masterson, who I think was the best general teacher of American history I ever saw.
I was trying to emulate him a lot of the time.
And I went in 1979 to
at the North Texas State University.
You had gotten into administration at Rice.
Oh, yeah, yes.

I'd gotten in, despite the fact that one year I shared an office with Walter Prescott Webb, who had left the University of Texas and retired, and he came to Rice, and he kept saying, now, no matter what they tell you, don't go into administration.
So, of course, I didn't listen to Walter Prescott Webb, and I should have.
Got into administration, became department chairman, which I hated, and dropped that job, and

In between, I got to go to England as the Harmsburg Professor of American History, which was a great year at Oxford, and came back and got stuck with being chairman again, because I wasn't there when they were selecting chairman.
You know how that is, don't you?
Yes.
And then the president of Rice left, Ken Pitzer, he went back to Stanford as president,
And I was selected as acting president of Rice University.
Apparently, again, for the reason that nobody else would take the job.
And I took the job for the- What year was that?
And I think I took the job for a reason that a lot of presidents take the job.
I was afraid of who else might get it.
So I was acting president for 18 months.
And then Norman Hackerman came from the University of Texas.
And I became Norman's provost at Rice and stayed in that job.
Let's see, I was in that job for a year and then I went for a year to West Point and was professor of military history at West Point for a year, 73 to 74.
Did you like that?
I loved it.
I had a wonder.
It was like dying and going to heaven for a military historian.
It was wonderful.
And then came back and stayed at, as
provost and finally academic vice president together until 1979.
My wife died in late 78, and that really changed my whole attitude about staying at Rice.
79, excuse me.
So two weeks after she died, the offer to go to North Texas came, and it was, at that time, a very great release for me to go.
And I went and had a great year and a half.
I thought North Texas was a wonderful place.
It was just lying fallow.
And it was.
And it is a good school, you know.
Yeah, I think it is, too.
And I had a wonderful time there.
I learned about one of the super music schools of the country, which is up there.
It really is great.
And I had a good time there.
And to tell you how I got to A&M, I can tell you exactly the first moment I heard about it.
Not about my original thoughts.
I'll come to those in a minute.
But I had gotten up early in the morning, and I was getting ready to go to the office in North Texas, and it was over.
It was about, oh, 7 o'clock.
It was a day like this, beautiful, clear blue sky, and sort of cool.
And Renee and I were sitting in the living room, looking out the window at the trees and having coffee.
And the phone rang, and it was Frank Hubert.
And I wish I could tell you the date.
I simply don't remember what the date was.
Frank said, it must have been sometime in early August, maybe.
But he said, I said, my God, Frank, what are you doing calling me at 7 o'clock in the morning?
I said, are you calling to tell me the name of the new president of A&M?
They had been debating this, and we'd read in the paper there were 200 candidates and all this kind of thing.
And he said, well, I hope I'm talking to you.
And I almost dropped the phone.
And I said, what?

and he said well the 200 candidates we had all busted so he said i threw my hat down on the table at the board meeting and i said i'm going to give you the name of the man who ought to be the president and he said i think they'll probably go take my recommendation if you're interested
Well, I said, I don't know.
You've got to give me a little time to know.
He said, I'm not going to give you any time to think.
You had not even given it any thought.
Not at all.
I'd been reading what they were doing, but it never crossed my mind.
And I said, well, I really am not going to tell you, Frank, what I think about it, but you can talk some more.
Tell me about the place and what you want and what the situation is.
Excuse me.
So he said, well, we are...
We need a president.
We've had a president for a year and a half or however long it had been.
It didn't work out for anybody and for him and for us.
And I'm the chancellor, and I have the job of selecting you.
And he said, if you're interested, I want you to go down to Dallas and meet with Bum Bright and John Blocker as soon as possible.
They were both members of the board, as you know.
So I said, well, I'll think about it.
He said, call me back in half an hour.
He did not give me much time.
So I went into the living room.
Renee said, what was that all about?
I said, well, I don't know exactly what happened, but I think I was just offered the presidency of Texas A&M University.
She said, you're joking.
And I said, no, I think that's what happened.
So the next thing I did was call Norman Hackman very early, right away.
He was already in the office, knowing Norm.
He'd been there for two hours.
And I told Norm what had happened and what did he think.
He said, well, they called me, and I suspect they're actually going to offer you the job.
And he said, now, I didn't think you ought to go to North Texas because I didn't think they had any money.
And there wasn't much you could do with the university.
But A&M has part of the available fund.
And something can be done there.
So I think you ought to seriously consider going.
So I called Frank back in about an hour, not half an hour, and said, well, I'll go down and see Bum.
But I said, I can't do it right away because Renee and I are going to China.
A group of presidents of state universities have been selected to go to China.
So we went to China.
And came back.
And then I went down to see Bum.
John, and I had a very interesting interview with them.
They asked me the same question one of them said, you asked, what do you think about A&M?
And I had thought I was probably asked that question, so I decided to be honest.
I said, this is no time to be coy, gentlemen.
You ought to really know what I think about A&M.
I said, my daughter is in A&M at the moment, and before she went, though, I had very low opinion.

I share the elitist view of all Rice people that no other university in the state was worth anything except perhaps Texas because of my own personal bias but A&M I thought was sort of a cow college and it was several grades above the University of Houston but not too many in my eye and I said I also have heard several times that the Board of Regents is impossible to work with
And no president told me straight out.
And I said, I don't think, as I understand it, nobody can survive the board.
So I think you ought to know that I am very dubious that you and I are going to get along very well.
I have a wonderful board at North Texas.
And they said, said, how can that be?
You've got 80 childs on the board.
And I said, that's right.
And I thought I'd have a lot of trouble with 80 childs.
But each meeting, he starts off by saying, we are here.
we have only one legitimate function, to hire or fire the president.
Do I hear a motion to fire the president?
He really did.
And hearing no such motion, our only other legitimate function is to ask him how we can help him.
I said, I have a wonderful board chairman, and I don't think I want to trade on that.
And they looked a little surprised, but I thought they were both very nice.
I was particularly impressed with John Blocker,
who I thought all along really knew what the university was.
I wasn't sure that Bum did, but I knew that Bum's heart was in the right place, and I could tell that from the interview.
And so it went along very well.
I was there two or three hours, two and a half hours, and they finally said, well, would you go up to Indianapolis and meet Art Hanson, who was then president of Purdue?
Excuse me.
And they said, he's going to be chancellor next year.
This was almost a year ahead.
But nobody knows him.
So you go up and see him.
So I went up and had an interview with Hanson.
I liked him very much.
It seemed to go very well.
And that's how I got the job.
I came back, and they offered it to me, and I took it.
Had the search been put on hold here during that time?
I'm trying to remember.
I'm trying to remember.
I was trying to.
The same thing was going through my mind.
Apparently, they'd run through a great number of candidates.
And I don't know whether it was on hold or whether it was just nothing had happened.
They just sort of sat for a while.
And I said, look, you can't really offer me this job.
And I can't take this job without visiting the university and talking to the faculty.
This doesn't make sense.
Well, that was a shock.
Apparently, that hadn't been done before.
So they arranged a visit for us to come down, Renee and me, and talk to various people.
I talked to various members of what was the old academic program council, do you remember?
And I didn't think I talked to enough faculty.
I was talking to administrators.
I kept talking to deans and people like, where is the faculty?
And they just never showed up.
There were some members of the faculty on that council, but not very many.
I still didn't feel that I had a,
a broad enough base of constituency to deal with.
But that seemed to be what, the way they worked it here, so.
I remember one engineer told me, well, why do you want to talk to the faculty?
That sort of shook me up, you know.
And so I took the job.
And the, go on, pick up a question.
Could you again comment on your perception of A&M at the time you, say, walk into your office, and your sense of what you would like to do or needed to be done at Texas A&M as president?
By the time I took the job, I had read an awful lot of material about A&M, including your history, by the way, that I had not seen before.
I'd read all kinds of material, you know, the catalog, the budget,
all kinds of data, and my impression was this, that A&M had all the elements to be a great university.
It had a good faculty.
It had an uneven faculty, but basically a good faculty.
I read all the dossiers of the faculty I could get my hands on, and I thought it had a fine
Its greatest reputation was in engineering and agriculture.
It had a coming reputation in science, but it hadn't made it.
Its liberal arts were depressing, and they made me feel very bad, for obviously personal reasons.
Its school of education fascinated me, because I had been brought up in the old attitude that schools of education were crap, and that they had no place on a
campus of a university.
Well, that was Frank Hubert's realm, and I still remember being shocked when they split education out of the arts and sciences and he went with education.
I could never understand that.
I know the feeling, but I was impressed as I looked at the College of Education with the quality of the faculty.
I didn't know that you could have research in education, but some people were doing it.
So when I got here, I knew a lot more about A&M than when I started.
And I was... And you probably knew a lot more about A&M than a lot of A&M types.
Well, undoubtedly, because I had really studied it.
You knew a hell of a lot more, but most of the faculty didn't know all this about A&M.
So I came with a feeling that...
I looked at the available fund and the PUF and realized that Norm was right.
There was a chance to do something here then.
I think it's all watered down now.
But then there was.
And the problem, of course, was going to be, who could I put in the administration to help me get it done?
Get what done?
Get what done?
What did I want to do?
Well, the first thing that occurred to me was that the president of the university ought to have a vision of an institution, for it anyway, one that he
He may be able to, he can articulate, but he may not be able to achieve, but he ought to be able to articulate a vision of the university.
And I could tell from A&M's reputation in things like agriculture and engineering that it had an opportunity to be an international institution.
So that's when I came up with the idea of a world university, not a world-class university, but a world university.
And I really worked toward that, trying to internationalize the institution.
And then I looked around at the administration, and you know, nobody wants to come in and shake the place up immediately.
You want to look around and see what you got to deal with.
And so I made a very careful study of all the colleges.
I went to every college and asked the dean to give me a whole day's briefing with the faculty and everybody.
So in a period of about six months, I knew a lot about every college.
And that was a most revealing experience.
And I knew a lot about the deans by then, too.
How did the A&M College structure, let's say, compare or differ from the other, North Texas, Rice, et cetera?
And this is a leading question that I have at home.
It compared very similar to the North Texas college structure, colleges of engineering and so forth.
Rice had an entirely different focus.
But coming from North Texas, I could relate to the college structure here easily enough.
Now, Rice has two different colleges, the residential college system and then the academic colleges.
So you get all mixed up between the two.
But I got a pretty good idea of what the institution was like.
And I liked what I saw in the deans.
I thought most of those were pretty good.
Strong deans.
Strong deans, yes.
And they're essential.
The provost, or the academic vice president, when I came, oh, my mind is leaking.
You will remember.
I can't help you at the moment.
I was thinking.
It'll come to me in a minute.
Oh, dear.
Anyway, it'll come back to me.
He said he'd stay until the end.
That's not Mac Prescott.
Yes, it was Mac Prescott.
And Mac said he'd stay for a year, but no longer.
Well, I liked Mac.
I thought he was damn good, and I wished he would stay home, but he obviously wasn't going to.
He made up his mind to go.
So I had to look around for an academic VP, and for another year, I stuck with Chuck McCandless, who was his deputy.
But I was looking for a provost, and finally came up with...
Gordon Eaton.
And Gordy and I got along just fine.
We were, we thought alike and that sort of thing.
Where'd you find Gordon?
In a search?
Well, we had a regular search.
That was another thing.
I started searches for administrators, which shocked everybody, you know.
I would put together a search committee with administrators and faculty members and consequently
Obviously this was iconoclastic.
People didn't do that at A&M.
And very soon I began to worry that the APC, I think that was what it was called, wasn't the body of people that I needed to deal with.
Those were the deans and department heads.
Yeah.
And you know, I needed to talk to the deans and department heads, but I couldn't find the faculty.
My whole orientation was, how can you run a university if you don't know what the faculty wants to do?
The faculty may have a view of the university you don't have.
And to me, the faculty is the heart of the university.
And if you haven't got them with you, you might as well quit.
Because ultimately, they're going to scuttle you.
But I couldn't find out who the faculty was and how to get their opinion.
And very shortly after I got here, I got all hooked up in
football crisis, as you may remember, with Tom Wilson and the coming of Jackie Sherrill.
And that was a disaster because I really, not a disaster, but it was eye-opening to me because it turned out I had really nothing to do with the athletic program.
Turns out the Board of Regents ran the athletic program.
And so I had a big fight with the Board about that.

I made a stand with Frank, and I told him that if they ran roughshod in and tried to put a new coach in without me being involved, I said, I know you have the veto, but if I'm not involved in the process, I quit.
And I wrote a letter to that effect and gave it to Frank and had a stormy session with the board.
But I said, look, you guys can't do this.
I said to Bum, this is what I told you when I was talking to you about coming here.
You are running the university, and you can't do that.
How long after you got here was that?
Do you remember?
It was about, let's see, we'd been through one football season.
I got here in September.
We went through the football season, and it was right at the end of that.
So it would have been about January, right after, yeah, January, February.
Did you have a meeting with the faculty about that time?
I did.
I'd forgotten that.
I'd forgotten that.
I'd forgotten that.
We all dropped our teeth about that time.
But you see, my own feeling was, Henry, I couldn't go on as president with the faculty thinking that I had been all screwed up in this football business and that I just couldn't let the faculty feel.
What I'm trying to say is I couldn't go on if the faculty didn't approve of what I had done.
And there wasn't a faculty senate to deal with.
So I called a convocation of the faculty.
And that may have been a precedent-setting meeting.
Well, I think it was.
And I think the faculty weren't prepared.
They didn't know what was going on.
And all of a sudden, there he is.
I think they were, as I was, but sort of hanging there.
Well, I didn't know what else to do.
It was interesting.
And I had no other constituents to deal with.
And I thought, well, if the faculty is going to say no, well, I'll quit.
And I don't think the faculty had ever been presented with that kind of choice before.
Well, and that led me to the faculty senate business.
OK, now where did that idea come from?
What was the precedent?
Did they have it in North Texas?
They had a faculty senate in North Texas.
Yes, indeed.
And they had a faculty council, it was called, at Rice, which was the same thing.
But I went on here.
And one day, a group of about three or four professors came in, led by Tom Kozik.
And it was after this board, this meeting, that I called.
And he said, well, you know, this meeting you called was very interesting.
It reminded me of a plan.
several of us came up with several years ago to try to push a faculty senate, which he said did not get very far.
And he said, since you seem to want faculty opinion, how do you feel about a faculty senate?
And I said, boy, I am all for it.
So he said, here.
He dusted off an old plan, literally, and handed it to me.
And he said, can you start with this?
So you know what happened?
I created a committee to look into the faculty senate.
Claude Davis was the chairman, who did a great job.
The committee did a wonderful job.
They had a hell of a time, too.
They worked very hard.
Worked very hard on it.
And they had a lot of resistance.
God almighty, you know.
That has changed.
I couldn't believe it.
I just couldn't believe it.
The engineering school came to pieces.
Veterinary medicine blew up, you know.
How could you do something like this?
We haven't done it this way before.
So I was very proud of that.
I think they did a wonderful job.
And as you know, we turned over all the functions of the old ABC to the Senate, course approval and all that sort of thing.
And I think they've done a great job.
OK, let me ask you about the faculty senate.
Do you think, how has that impacted, let's say, on the quality and the character of the university?
Well, I'm probably not the best one to ask that.
You ought to ask the faculty, I guess.
But what I think, let me give you my impression.
Remember, I'll give you a biased impression because I was so much in favor of the Senate.
I thought all along that the university, if it was going to become a first-class institution,
couldn't get there with, you couldn't hire the right kind of faculty if you didn't get into the 20th century administratively.
You know, you talk to good faculty everywhere, and they always ask about faculty representation, faculty governance, and all this kind of thing.
So I thought the Senate was essential for recruiting faculty.
I thought it was essential, too, as an organization through which the administration
could make its plans known, and could ask advice and help of the faculty.
I really saw the Senate as a two-way street.
Did it work that way?
It did work that way.
Not always, but essentially.
And I told that committee that was making up, creating the Senate at their last meeting, I said, look, when this Senate is going, the first time I say to myself, Jesus Christ, why did I do this?
You are a success.
And it took about a year, but then I started saying it frequently.
Yes, yes.
And I meant that, and I think that's true.
Do you think there was a tangible result in better recruiting?
Did you sense that?
I think so.
I think so.
A lot of the fact, I always sat in on recruiting a full professor.
I couldn't do it further down, and I didn't think it was really my business.
Sure.
But I thought full professors... You did interview the full professors?
Yes, I thought I ought to look at those.
And several of them would say, do you have a faculty center?
And I think that was very important.
And through the Senate, for instance, we worked on, Gordy and I worked on getting the core curriculum approved.
And I wrote to the Senate and suggested they look at the core curriculum.
And lo and behold, I think they came up with a fine core curriculum.
And they did it.
I was really proud of that.
I think one of the main achievements of my administration was the faculty senate.
I was going to say, I assume that.
Yeah.
What about the academic recasting or redirection or thrusting that you were trying to achieve as president?
Where were you trying to work?
I was trying to work at... Or does a president really have a capability to sit there and shape those kind of things very... You can think about it.
You can think about it.
But you can't do them until the opportunity comes.
I wanted very strong leadership in two areas where we had a real problem.
You will recall that agriculture and engineering had gotten into a serious split of authority
The dean, for instance, the dean of agriculture had almost no authority.
He was the academic dean, but he didn't have any research money.
Remember, it all went off to the experiment station.
And my big problem, I was trying to think very early on how you get it back together.
The experiment stations and the engineering experiment stations
had been siphoned off to the system, you may remember.
Well, how can you bifurcate the College of Engineering and Agriculture that way?
It emasculates the university side, and it creates a monster from the standpoint of the research side.
If you were a professor of agriculture, and you also had a joint appointment in the experiment station, which you would if you wanted to do research, where did your loyalty lie?
It was with the man who had the money.
And so it was a terrible mess.
And the only solution, the obvious one I wanted to achieve, was to get it back to the university and have the system say a flag on it and take it back.
Well, Frank wasn't about to do that because he'd fought the whole battle of trying to get it saved in the first place.
It was old history.
You know about that.
Hanson knew where it ought to be in the university, but he didn't want to give it up.
Sure, that's right.
And I could see that happening.
And I kept saying, Art, you know where it ought to be in the university.
Oh, I know, I know, but it's just going to take a little while to get this done.
So what we did was come up with this sort of curious two-hatted creature
The first one was Donald McDonald, who you remember was a professor of engineering, and we made him, got Art to agree to this, made him dean of engineering and deputy chancellor for engineering.
He was acting in both capacities.
So he had two hats, but it gave him what amounted to the power of one office.
And that worked.
So we worked that in agriculture.
Perry, got Perry to do that.
And that, I think, was an ingenious dodge that worked.
And then the problem was to get the right person.
Donald didn't want to keep it.
Donald, you know, he took a hell of a beating in that job.
It was terrible.
because the faculty didn't understand it and the faculty didn't want it.
There was a lot of contention.
You remember.
You remember.
It was really a mess.
And then everybody thought Nichols were at stake, too.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
They sure were.
Yeah.
And it was a mess.
And he took a real pounding.
I thought he ought to wear a flak jacket every day over at the engineering school.
So the problem was to get the right people.
And that's where the faculty senate helped, because we had one.
Gordy and I put together a search committee to look for both a dean and vice chancellor of engineering and of agriculture.
And we had a hell of a time recruiting Herb Richardson, but we did it.
Herb was dean of engineering, you know, at MIT.
And it turns out that he was actually slated to be president.
But I think the thing that saved us was he didn't know that.
And we didn't either.
Have you ever told him that?
No.
And so it was sort of like a soap opera.
Every week we would wonder how we were doing in recruiting Herb Richardson.
We'd have him and then we wouldn't have him.
It's like landing a great big fish.
And Gordy and I both knew that.
We knew that if we could land Herb Richardson, steal the dean of engineering from MIT, we had made it.
A&M had made it.
And it was vital that we get him.
So then we went to get Charlie Arnson for agriculture, and he was with, oh, what's that big company that he came from?
He was their research director.
It's a big ag corporation, and I can't think of the name.
Anyway, but again, he was a member of the National Academy of Sciences, and Herb was a member of the National Academy of Engineering.
That's the kind of quality we were looking for.
And getting them both was a big moment.
And to me, it represented the arrival of Texas A&M on the national scene.
Good.
Now, how are you and Hanson collaborating or not?
Very well.
Very well.
Art's problem, and I say this with affection because I like Art, was he could never make a decision.
Gordy came back from some meeting after we had been announced he was coming here, and he'd run into somebody from Georgia Tech.
You know, he'd been at Georgia Tech before, Hanson had.
And he said, the man looked at him and said, has Art made a decision yet?
And that was true.
That was true.
But he was, Hanson knew what a university ought to be, and that's what counted.
So when you'd go in and you'd tell him, look, we're trying to recruit somebody like Herb Richardson, he understood that.
Now, where is the board?
right now in all of this?
The board was very supportive of this kind of thing.
As long as you and Hansen were basically together and presented a united front.
Yeah, yeah.

One of the board members, Dooley Bell, whose name you may remember, told me one time, I'd been telling the board that one of my objectives was to get either raised internally or hire a Nobel laureate.
because I thought that a great research university wasn't one unless it could recruit at that level.
And he told me one day, he says, by God, you better recruit that Nobel laureate fast, because people are getting mad at the way you're recruiting all these highfalutin faculty members.
But that made me feel good.
That meant the board was concerned and knew what I was trying to do.
Now, they might not like it, but they understood it.
And Hanson understood it, and he explained it to them, what we were trying to do.
So we got those two, and then I went after... Is Bum still... Bum is still chairman of the board.
Then one day Perry called, and he said, how much do you really want to recruit a Nobel laureate?
I said, pretty much, Perry.
He said, well, I think we have a shot at Norman Borlaug.
And oh my God, that was... Then we got Norman, as you know,
And that was another great step forward.
Then we got Derek Barton in chemistry.
And that was another great shot in the arm for us.
And you know, my feeling was that if you could recruit at that level, Henry, you didn't have to worry about being a national institution anymore.
Right.
Or a world.
That's right.
People knew you.
That's right.
And you know, we recruited a wonderful black
playwright who was a Pulitzer Prize winner.
Then we began to hit that kind of stride.
These are sort of tangential questions, I guess.
What's your relationship, let's say, with the former Students' Organization about this time?
Is there any collaboration, association, friction, et cetera?
All of the above.
All of the above.
A lot of change.
A lot of change on the campus.
Many old eggs were not at all sure that this was the right way to go.
